"58a_base64.mst — Base64 (RFC 4648, standard alphabet + padding). A library
 gap fill: encoding only, for exactly one job — crossing an arbitrary
 ByteArray (a Pixmap's raw RGBA bytes) over a String-only channel, the same
 reason the web GUI's own Canvas pixel path base64s (docs/CANVAS.md §6a:
 'evaluateJavaScript carries a source string, not binary'). The Cocoa GUI's
 ObjC bridge has the identical shape: an `@`-typed outbound argument marshals
 a Smalltalk String to NSString, but there is no ByteArray->NSData case
 (src/runtime/objc_bridge.rs's `ObjcArg::Id` arm) — encoding here, decoding
 host-side (Rust), needs no VM/bridge change at all.

 Lettered file (matching 04a_blockclosure.mst's own precedent): 01-62 are
 fully packed (world/cocoaui.list's own header note), and this is a general
 codec, not Cocoa-specific, so it belongs in the base world, not 63+."
Object subclass: Base64 [
    Base64 class >> alphabet [
        ^'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789+/'
    ]
    "Standard RFC 4648 encode with '=' padding. aByteArray may be any
     indexable byte collection (ByteArray, or a String read as bytes)."
    Base64 class >> encode: bytes [
        | alpha out n i b0 b1 b2 tail |
        alpha := self alphabet.
        out := WriteStream on: String new.
        n := bytes size.
        i := 1.
        [ i + 2 <= n ] whileTrue: [
            b0 := bytes at: i. b1 := bytes at: i + 1. b2 := bytes at: i + 2.
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (b0 bitShift: -2) + 1).
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (((b0 bitAnd: 3) bitShift: 4) bitOr: (b1 bitShift: -4)) + 1).
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (((b1 bitAnd: 15) bitShift: 2) bitOr: (b2 bitShift: -6)) + 1).
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (b2 bitAnd: 63) + 1).
            i := i + 3 ].
        tail := n - i + 1.
        tail = 1 ifTrue: [
            b0 := bytes at: i.
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (b0 bitShift: -2) + 1).
            out nextPut: (alpha at: ((b0 bitAnd: 3) bitShift: 4) + 1).
            out nextPutAll: '==' ].
        tail = 2 ifTrue: [
            b0 := bytes at: i. b1 := bytes at: i + 1.
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (b0 bitShift: -2) + 1).
            out nextPut: (alpha at: (((b0 bitAnd: 3) bitShift: 4) bitOr: (b1 bitShift: -4)) + 1).
            out nextPut: (alpha at: ((b1 bitAnd: 15) bitShift: 2) + 1).
            out nextPutAll: '=' ].
        ^out contents
    ]
]

"Reopen Pixmap (world/36 — loads long before Base64 above, so this couldn't
 live there: naming Base64 at file 36's load point would be a compile-time
 undeclared-global error). SAME FILE as Base64 itself (not Cocoa-only): a
 `Worker uiDoit:`-relayed expression runs on the PRIMARY, which boots ONLY
 world.list — NEVER cocoaui.list (that file's own header comment: 'Loaded
 ONLY by the UI worker... NEVER from world/world.list') — so a Cocoa-only
 placement would DNU there. A DNU inside a doit is SILENT by design (world/47
 serveUiDoit:'s own contract: 'unwinds the whole dispatch and sends no
 reply'), which is exactly how this bug first showed up: the Cocoa Canvas
 tab's Mandelbrot button hung at 'computing…' forever with nothing logged."
Object subclass: Pixmap [
    "Base64 of the raw RGBA bytes — the pixel-buffer transport
     docs/CANVAS.md §6a describes; the Cocoa GUI's showCanvasPixelsOn:
     base64:width:height: (cocoa_gui/src/canvas.rs) consumes it directly."
    asCanvasBase64 [ ^Base64 encode: self bytes ]
]
